Nvidia Corporation, founded in 1993 by Jensen Huang, Chris Malachowsky, and Curtis Priem, began as a pioneer in graphics processing technology. Initially focusing on producing graphics cards for gaming and multimedia PCs, Nvidia launched its first product, the NV1, in 1995. Though not widely successful, it set the foundation for future advancements.

The breakthrough came in 1999 with the release of the GeForce 256, marketed as the world’s first graphics processing unit (GPU). This innovation redefined 3D gaming and established Nvidia as a leader in graphics technology. Over the 2000s, Nvidia expanded through strategic acquisitions, including 3dfx in 2000 and Ageia in 2008, gaining access to new technologies like GPU-accelerated physics processing.

In the 2010s, Nvidia’s focus extended beyond gaming to include high-performance computing, artificial intelligence (AI), and deep learning. Its CUDA architecture, launched in 2006, enabled GPUs to handle complex AI workloads, gaining widespread adoption in research and enterprise sectors.

The company’s role became especially prominent in the AI boom of the 2020s, as its GPUs powered machine learning systems in everything from autonomous vehicles to data centers. Nvidia further entered the system-on-chip (SoC) space with its Tegra processors and made forays into automotive, edge computing, and cloud gaming with services like GeForce NOW.

In 2020, Nvidia announced its intent to acquire Arm Ltd., though regulatory hurdles eventually prevented the deal. Despite this, Nvidia remains a dominant force in GPU and AI technology, shaping the future of computing across multiple industries.

claude
